Sure — here’s a matching **light‑mode CSS snippet** you can drop in place of the dark‑mode styles if you plan to print or display it on a projector.  
It keeps the same spacing and fonts but switches to high‑contrast dark text on a pale background:

```html
<style>
  body{
    font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;
    line-height: 1.6;
    background: #FFFFFF;
    color: #000000;
    margin: 2em;
  }
  h1,h2{
    color: #004C99;     /* calm blue for headings */
  }
  a{
    color: #003399;
    text-decoration: underline;
  }
  a:hover{
    color: #0000FF;
  }
  section{margin-bottom: 2em;}
  footer{
    margin-top: 2em;
    font-size: 0.9em;
    color: #333333;
  }
</style>
```

You can copy‑paste this style block into the `<head>` section of that HTML file instead of the dark one.  
When printed, it stays readable with plenty of white space and still highlights the hotline numbers for visibility.

